{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506944"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:48:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:48:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2592"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2592"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.03,0.04,0.72,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2592"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96780"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2592"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2592"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79395"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"675"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2769"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2894"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28001"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33181"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49342"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96780"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old Aboriginal woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a widespread rash over her body, which has been present for about seven days. She feels feverish and has some painful lumps in her neck. She has felt fatigued for the past month. She has no chest pain or joint pain. She has a medical history of mild asthma but takes no regular medications. She is sexually active with male partners and is inconsistent with barrier contraception. She denies any drug use and has no tattoos.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, pulse 90/min, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.4\u00b0C. There are discrete, erythematous maculopapular lesions over her trunk. This rash is also present on the soles of her feet. She has several enlarged and tender cervical lymph nodes. There are no other lumps or rashes on dermatological assessment. Her cardiorespiratory examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rheumatic fever","Infective endocarditis","Lymphoma","Syphilis","Pharyngitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a common presentation and ideally the doctor would take a more detailed history. Critically, there are minimal conditions which cause a widespread rash that also includes the palms or soles of feet. In combination with other symptoms, \u003Cstrong\u003Esecondary syphilis\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe reasons for the increase in incidence of syphilis in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities is unclear, but could be attributed to lack of access to health care, and also to growing resistance of \u003Cem\u003ET. pallidum\u003C/em\u003E to another commonly used antibiotic (azithromycin) used to treat other sexually transmitted infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt can present with the above rash, fever, lymphadenopathy, alopecia or condylomata lata. It typically lasts 3-12 weeks and occurs after resolution of primary syphilis. Many patients will not be aware of having primary syphilis as it is a painless ulcer that can be internal wherever syphilis was in contact with mucosal membranes (oropharynx, vagina, rectum etc.).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatic fever\u003C/strong\u003E has a different rash (erythema marginosum) and there is no joint pain/inflammation, chest pain or subcutaneous nodules.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfective endocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely as there are no immunological or vascular signs. Further, there is no source of bacteraemia such as IV drug use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPharyngitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a reasonable differential but would normally have a shorter clinical course and is unlikely to cause this type of rash, and acutely would have an erythematous pharynx. It would also be more common in a younger patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymphoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a good differential especially if the lymphadenopathy failed to resolve with antibiotic treatment and should be considered in young patients. However, the risk factors for syphilis and the rash make it the most likely differential.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKey considerations for Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander people in syphilis management include cultural safety in healthcare, offering choice of clinician gender, involvement of Aboriginal Health Practitioners, and culturally appropriate contact tracing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Secondary syphilis presents with a widespread maculopapular rash that includes the palms and soles, along with fever, lymphadenopathy, and fatigue.","Syphilis rates are increasing in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander communities, requiring culturally safe approaches to testing and treatment.","Cultural safety and involvement of Aboriginal Health Practitioners are essential components of effective syphilis management in Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander patients."],"references":["Nyatsanza F, Tipple C. Syphilis: presentations in general medicine. Clin Med (Lond). 2016; 16(2): 184-188.","Ngan V, Oakley A. Syphilis. New Zealand: DermNet NZ; 2003 [updated 2020; cited 2021 May 19]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/syphilis/.","Australian STI Management Guidelines for Use in Primary Care. Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander People (2024). Available at: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/populations-and-situations/aboriginal-and-torres-strait-islander-people/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79395"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2592"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79395"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T21:53:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-25T09:24:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2592"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96780"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":nul